taenia colialso known as longitudinal band of large intestine muscularis The taeniae coli (also teniae coli) are three separate longitudinal ribbons of smooth muscle on the outside of the ascending, transverse, descending and sigmoid colons. They are visible, and can be seen just below the serosa or fibrosa. They are the Mesocolic, Free and Omental Coli. The teniae coli contracts length wise to produce the haustra, the bulges in the colon. The bands converge at the root of the vermiform appendix and the rectum. These bands correspond to the outer layer of the muscularis externa, in other portions of the digestive tract.
endothelium of peritubular capillaryalso known as peritubular capillary endothelium An endothelium that is part of a peritubular capillary.

hepatoduodenal ligamentalso known as ligamentum hepatoduodenale The hepatoduodenal ligament is the portion of the lesser omentum extending between the porta hepatis of the liver and the superior part of the duodenum.
skeleton of pelvic complex The collection of all skeletal elements in a pelvic complex - i.e. the combination of free limb or fin plus pelvic girdle.

dorsal part of neckalso known as back of neck; nape of neck; neck back; nucha; nuchal region; posterior cervical region; posterior neck region; posterior part of neck; regio cervicalis posterior The posterior region of the neck, including the suboccipital region.

muscle layer of colonalso known as colonic muscularis propria; muscular coat of colon; muscular layer of colon; muscularis externa of colon; tunica muscularis coli A muscular coat that is part of a colon.
muscularis mucosae of duodenumalso known as lamina muscularis of duodenal mucous membrane; lamina muscularis of duodenum A muscularis mucosa that is part of a duodenum.
serosa of appendixalso known as appendiceal serosa; appendix serosa; serosa of vermiform appendix; visceral peritoneum of vermiform appendix A serous membrane that is part of a vermiform appendix.

ampulla of uterine tubealso known as uterine tube ampulla; ampulla of fallopian tube; ampulla of oviduct; ampulla tubae uterinae The ampulla is the second portion of the uterine tube. It is an intermediate dilated portion, which curves over the ovary. It is the most common site of human fertilization. The word ampulla is from the Latin for flask.

sulcus of brainalso known as cerebral sulci A depression or fissure in the surface of the brain. It surrounds the gyri, creating the characteristic appearance of the brain in humans and other large mammals.
vein of abdomenalso known as abdominal vein A vein that is part of a abdomen.

penicillar arteriolealso known as penicilli; penicillus One of the small straight arteries of the red pulp of the spleen; a branch of the spleen central artery that supplies the red pulp[WP,modified].

superior phrenic arteryalso known as arteria phrenicea superioris; arteriae phrenicae superiores A phrenic artery that arises from the lower part of the thoracic aorta and is distributed to the posterior part of the upper surface of the diaphragm, and anastomoses with the musculophrenic and pericardiacophrenic arteries.
vein of lipalso known as labial vein of face; lip vein; vena labialis A vein that drains a lip.
external pudendal arteryalso known as arteriae pudendae externa; arteriae pudendales externa Either the superficial or deep external pudendal arteries.

coronary ligament of liveralso known as coronary ligament; ligamentum coronarium; ligamentum coronarium hepatis The coronary ligament of the liver refers to parts of the peritoneal reflections that hold the liver to the inferior surface of the diaphragm.
ligament of liveralso known as hepatic ligament; liver ligament A nonskeletal ligament that is part of a liver.
systemic veinalso known as systemic venous tree organ part Any vein within the general circulation that transports blood back to the right atrium of the heart.
soleal veinalso known as soleus vein; vein of soleus muscle; vena solealis A vein that drains the soleus.
gastrocnemius veinalso known as vein of gastrocnemius muscle; vena gastrocnemii A vein that drains the gastrocnemius.
vein of genicular venous plexus vein of genicular venous plexus

choroidal arteryalso known as artery of choroid plexus; choroid artery One of two arteries (anterior and posterior choroidal artery) that supply blood to the choroid plexus, optic tract, hippocampus, globus pallidus, and other various brain regions.

ovarian cortexalso known as cortex of ovary; cortex ovarii (zona parenchymatosa) The layer of the ovarian stroma lying immediately beneath the tunica albuginea, composed of connective tissue cells and fibers, among which are scattered primary and secondary (antral) follicles in various stages of development; the cortex varies in thickness according to the age of the individual, becoming thinner with advancing years; included in the follicles are the cumulus oophorus, membrana granulosa (and the granulosa cells inside it), corona radiata, zona pellucida, and primary oocyte; the zona pellucida, theca of follicle, antrum and liquor folliculi are also contained in the follicle; also in the cortex is the corpus luteum derived from the follicles.

ovarian medullaalso known as medulla of ovary; medulla ovarii (zona vasculosa) Highly vascular stroma found in the center of the ovary that forms from embryonic mesenchyme and contains blood vessels, lymphatic vessels, and nerves; this stroma forms the tissue of the hilum by which the ovarian ligament is attached, and through which the blood vessels enter; it does not contain any ovarian follicles.
serous acinusalso known as acinus of serous gland The secretory unit of a serous gland. The acinar portion is composed of serous secreting cells.

crypt of Lieberkuhn of colonalso known as colonic crypt; colonic crypt of Lieberkuhn An intestinal crypt that is located in the colon. The colonic crypts of Lieberkühn are straight and unbranched and lined largely with goblet cells.
epidermal ridge of digit The grooves in the outermost layer of skin on the palms of the hands and soles of the feet where sweat glands open.

subdivision of oviductalso known as subdivision of oviduct; subdivision of uterine tube; uterine tube zone; zone of uterine tube A section through the tube or network of tubes that connects the ovaries to the outside of the body.
subdivision of tube subdivision of tube
metapodium bone 1also known as metapodium 1; metapodium I A metapodium bone that is part of a digit 1 plus metapodial segment.
metapodium bone 2also known as metapodium 2; metapodium II A metapodium bone that is part of a digit 2 plus metapodial segment.
metapodium bone 3also known as 3rd metapodium bone; metapodial bone III; metapodium 3; metapodium III A metapodial bone that is associated with digit III.
metapodium bone 4also known as metapodium 4; metapodium IV A metapodium bone that is part of a digit 4 plus metapodial segment.
metapodium bone 5also known as metapodium 5; metapodium V A metapodium bone that is part of a digit 5 plus metapodial segment.

short bone Short bones are designated as those bones that are as wide as they are long. Their primary function is to provide support and stability with little to no movement. They are one of five types of bones: long, short, flat, irregular and sesamoid. Examples of these bones include the tarsals in the foot and the carpals in the hand.

sesamoid elementalso known as sesamoid Ossicle that develops within bands of dense, regular connective tissue (e.g., tendons and ligaments). Sesamoids are generally located proximate to a bony prominence, over which the dense regular connective tissue wraps, and/or a joint or articulation.
epithelium of intestinal villusalso known as intestinal villus epithelium An epithelium that is part of a intestinal villus.

duodenal ampullaalso known as bulbus (duodenum); ampulla (duodenum); ampulla duodeni; ampulla of duodenum; bulbus duodeni; duodenal cap; duodenal cap viewed radiologically The very first part of the duodenum which is slightly dilated.

masseteric arteryalso known as arteria masseterica The masseteric artery is small and passes laterally through the mandibular notch to the deep surface of the masseter muscle, which it supplies. It anastomoses with the masseteric branches of the external maxillary artery and with the transverse facial artery.
foramen of skullalso known as foramen of skull Anatomical space that is an opening in a bone of the skull.
tonsil germinal center A germinal center that is part of a tonsil.

tonsil epithelium The epithelium that forms the surface of the tonsil dips into the underlying connective tissue in numerous places, forming crypts kown as tonsillar crypts. Stratified squamous epithelium, that may be heavily infiltrated by lymphocytes. Epithelial cells are present in the germinal as well as in the periphery of the nodule.

main body axis A principle subdivision of an organism that includes all structures along the primary axis, typically the anterior-posterior axis, from head to tail, including structures of the body proper where present (for example, ribs), but excluding appendages.
body proper The region of the organism associated with the visceral organs.
integumentary projection Anatomical projection that is part of the integumentl system.
integumentary system layer An organ component layer that is part of a integumental system.
cervical os One of two openings in the uterine cervix.
internal cervical os Opening of uterine cervix into the body of the uterus.
external cervical osalso known as external os of uterus; ostium uteri Opening of uterine cervix into the vagina.
cervical cavityalso known as lumen of cervix of uterus The cavity formed by the walls of the cervix.

digestive system elementalso known as digestive organ; digestive system organ Any of the organs or elements that are part of the digestive system. Examples: tongue, esophagus, spleen, crop, lunge feeding organ, tooth elements.

frontal process of maxillaalso known as processus frontalis (maxilla) A plate of bone from the maxilla that that projects upward, medialward, and backward, by the side of the nose, forming part of its lateral boundary[WP,modified].
great vessel of heartalso known as great vessel of thorax Great vessels is a term used to refer collectively to the large vessels that bring blood to and from the heart.
left nipple A nipple that is in_the_left_side_of a body proper.
right nipple A nipple that is in_the_right_side_of a body proper.
intrinsic muscle of manusalso known as intrinsic hand muscle; intrinsic muscle of hand Any of the intrinsic muscles of the manus (hand).
hypothenar muscle Any of three muscles of the palm that control the motion of the little finger.
intrinsic muscle of pesalso known as intrinsic muscle of foot Any of the intrinsic muscles of the pes (foot).

adductor hallucis musclealso known as adductor hallucis The Adductor hallucis (Adductor obliquus hallucis) arises by two headsboblique and transverse and is responsible for adducting the big toe. It is innervated by the lateral plantar nerve. It evolved from the contrahens I muscle as Man's ancestors' thumbs and big toes became opposable.

flexor digitorum brevis musclealso known as flexor digitorum brevis; flexor digitorum brevis of foot; musculus flexor digitorum brevis The flexor digitorum brevis lies in the middle of the sole of the foot, immediately above the central part of the plantar aponeurosis, with which it is firmly united. Its deep surface is separated from the lateral plantar vessels and nerves by a thin layer of fascia.
proximal mesopodial bone A proximal mesopodial endochondral element that is composed primarily of a bone tissue.

renal venous blood vesselalso known as kidney venous blood vessel; venous blood vessel of kidney Any member of the network of tubes that return blood from the renal tissues to the systemic circulation.

cardiac ganglionalso known as cardiac ganglia set; cardiac ganglion of Wrisberg; ganglia cardiaca; ganglion of Wrisberg; Wrisberg ganglion Any of the parasympathetic ganglia of the cardiac plexus between the arch of the aorta and the bifurcation of the pulmonary artery.

thoracic skeletonalso known as skeleton of thorax; thoracic part of axial skeleton; thoracic skeleton Subdivision of skeletal system that consists of all skeletal elements in the thoracic region of the trunk. In most vertebrates this is the rib cage and sternum.

subdivision of spinal cord central canalalso known as regional part of spinal cord central canal A subdivision of the central canal of the spinal cord along its anterior-posterior axis. This is typically subdivided into cervical, thoracic, lumbar and sacral segments.

thoracic division of spinal cord central canalalso known as thoracic spinal cord central canal Part of spinal cord central canal contained in the thoracic spinal cord. It is continuous rostrally with the cervical spinal cord central canal and caudally with the lumbar spinal cord central canal.

lumbar division of spinal cord central canalalso known as lumbar spinal cord central canal Part of central canal lying within the lumbar spinal cord. It is continuous rostrally with the central canal of the thoracic spinal cord and caudally with the central canal of the sacral spinal cord.

dorsal gray commissure of spinal cordalso known as commissura grisea posterior medullae spinalis; dorsal gray commissure; dorsal grey commissure of spinal cord; posterior grey commissure of spinal cord; spinal cord posterior gray commissure The part of the gray commissure in the spinal central gray posterior to the central canal of the spinal cord.

occipital gyrus A gyrus that is part of a occipital lobe.

cerebrocerebellumalso known as cerebellum lateral hemisphere; cerebellum lateral zone; neocerebellum; pontocerebellum The part of the cerebellar cortex that receives input from the cerebral cortex via axons from the pontine relay nuclei.
white matter of medulla oblongataalso known as substantia alba medullae oblongatae; white matter of medulla; white substance of medulla A white matter that is part of a medulla oblongata.

pterygoid plexusalso known as plexus venosus pterygoideus; pterygoid venous plexus The pterygoid plexus is a venous plexus of considerable size, and is situated between the temporalis muscle and lateral pterygoid muscle, and partly between the two pterygoid muscles.

angular vein The angular vein formed by the junction of the frontal vein and supraorbital vein, runs obliquely downward, on the side of the root of the nose, to the level of the lower margin of the orbit, where it becomes the anterior facial vein. It receives the external nasal veins of the ala nasi, and communicates with the superior ophthalmic vein through the nasofrontal vein, thus establishing an important anastomosis between the anterior facial vein and the cavernous sinus.

left gastric veinalso known as vena gastrica sinistra The Left gastric vein (or coronary vein) carries blood low in Oxygen, tributaries derived from both surfaces of the stomach; it runs from right to left along the lesser curvature of the stomach, between the two layers of the lesser omentum, to the esophageal opening of the stomach, where it receives some esophageal veins. It then turns backward and passes from left to right behind the omental bursa and drains into the portal vein. Esophageal and paraesophageal varices are primarily supplied by the left gastric vein and typically drain into the azygos/hemiazygos venous system.

right gastric veinalso known as vena gastrica dextra The right gastric vein, also known as the pyloric vein, drains blood from the lesser curvature of the stomach into the hepatic portal vein. It is part of the portal circulation.
superficial epigastric vein The superficial epigastric vein is a vein which travels with the superficial epigastric artery. It joins the accessory saphenous vein near the fossa ovalis.
inferior alveolar artery inferior alveolar artery

posterior auricular artery The posterior auricular artery is a small artery and arises from the external carotid artery, above the Digastric muscle and Stylohyoid muscle, opposite the apex of the styloid process. It ascends posteriorly beneath the parotid gland, along the styloid process of the temporal bone, between the cartilage of the ear and the mastoid process of the temporal bone along the lateral side of the head. The posterior auricular artery supplies blood to the scalp posterior to the auricle and to the auricle itself.

deep auricular artery The deep auricular artery often arises in common with the anterior tympanic artery. It ascends in the substance of the parotid gland, behind the temporomandibular articulation, pierces the cartilaginous or bony wall of the external acoustic meatus, and supplies its cuticular lining and the outer surface of the tympanic membrane. It gives a branch to the temporomandibular joint.
anterior choroidal artery The anterior choroidal artery originates from the internal carotid artery, though it also rarely arises from the middle cerebral artery.
anal membrane ectodermal component A unilaminar epithelium that develops_from a ectoderm and is part of a anal region.
interlobular duct A duct that is located between lobules, within the thin connective tissue septa that separate lobules. All interlobular ducts are excretory.
mucous acinusalso known as acinus of mucuous gland; mucus acinus The secretory unit of a mucous gland. The acinar portion is composed of mucous secreting cells.

intralobular duct A duct that is located within a lobule, with no more connective tissue intervening between ducts and secretory units (i.e., acini or tubules) than between adjacent secretory units. Intercalated and striated ducts are intralobular.
intercalated duct A small duct which drains individual secretory units. These are usually inconspicuous, lined by a simple epithelium consisting of low cuboidal cells.
intercalated duct of pancreasalso known as ductus intercalatus (pancreas); pancreatic ductule An intercalated duct that is part of a pancreas.
superior palpebral vein A blood vessel that drains from from an upper eyelid.
palpebral vein A blood vessel that drains from from an eyelid.
palpebral artery An artery that supplies blood to an eyelid.
lateral palpebral arteryalso known as lateral palpebral branch of ophthalmic artery The lateral palpebral arteries are small arteries which supply the eyelid.

medial palpebral arteryalso known as medial palpebral branch of ophthalmic artery The medial palpebral arteries (internal palpebral arteries) are arteries of the head. They are two in number, superior and inferior, arise from the ophthalmic, opposite the pulley of the Obliquus superior.
pectoral appendage muscle Any muscle organ that is part of a pectoral appendage (forelimb or pectoral fin).
pelvic appendage muscle Any muscle organ that is part of a pelvic appendage (hindlimb or pelvic fin).

vastus intermedius The Vastus intermedius (Cruraeus) arises from the front and lateral surfaces of the body of the femur in its upper two-thirds, sitting under Rectus Femoris and from the lower part of the lateral intermuscular septum. Its fibers end in a superficial aponeurosis, which forms the deep part of the Quadriceps femoris tendon. The Vastus medialis and Vastus intermedius appear to be inseparably united, but when the Rectus femoris has been reflected a narrow interval will be observed extending upward from the medial border of the patella between the two muscles, and the separation may be continued as far as the lower part of the intertrochanteric line, where, however, the two muscles are frequently continuous.
brainstem white matter White matter that is part of a brainstem [Automatically generated definition].

skeletal muscle organ, vertebrate A muscle organ that consists of skeletal muscle tissue ensheathed in epimysium, that develops from myotome and that is innervated by some somatic motor neuron. Skeletal muscles are typically attached (via a tendon) to a bone but there are exceptions (e.g. intrinsic tongue muscles).

anterolateral ligament of kneealso known as (mid-third) lateral capsular ligament; ALL; anterolateral ligament; capsulo-osseous layer of the iliotibial band; ligament of Segond A ligament on the lateral aspect of the human knee, anterior to the fibular collateral ligament.

intersegmental pulmonary veinalso known as infrasegmental part of pulmonary vein; intersegmental part of pulmonary vein; partes intersegmentales venarum pulmonum A vein receiving blood from adjacent bronchopulmonary segments; it emerges from the inferior margin of a segment to become a tributary of a branch of a pulmonary vein.
