main lactiferous duct main lactiferous duct
terminal branch of ophthalmic artery The two terminal branches of the ophthalmic artery in humans are the dorsal nasal artery and the supratrochlear artery.

zygomatico-orbital artery The middle temporal artery occasionally gives off a zygomatico-orbital branch, which runs along the upper border of the zygomatic arch, between the two layers of the temporal fascia, to the lateral angle of the orbit. This branch, which may arise directly from the superficial temporal artery, supplies the Orbicularis oculi, and anastomoses with the lacrimal and palpebral branches of the ophthalmic artery.

supraorbital arteryalso known as arteria supraorbitalis; supra-orbital artery; supraorbital artery The supraorbital artery is an artery of the head. It springs from the ophthalmic artery as that vessel is crossing over to the medial side of the optic nerve.

uterine spiral arteryalso known as endometrial spiral arteriole; endometrial spiral artery A corkscrew-like artery in premenstrual or progestational endometrium; uterine spiral arteries play a vital role in supplying nutrients to the placenta and fetus, and are thus remodeled into highly dilated inelastic vessels by the action of invading trophoblast (physiological change).
endometrial blood vesselalso known as blood vessel of endometrium A blood vessel that is part of a endometrium.

helicine branch of uterine arteryalso known as arcuate artery of uterus; helicine artery of uterus; rami helicini uterinae The helicine branches of uterine artery (or helicine arterioles, or spiral arteries) are small arteries which temporarily supply the endometrium of the uterus during the luteal phase of the menstrual cycle. In histology, identifying the presence of these arteries is one of the most useful techniques in identifying the phase of the cycle.

helicine artery of penisalso known as arteriae helicinae penis The helicine arteries of penis are arteries in the penis. They are found in the corpora cavernosa penis. They are involved in the process of erection.
helicine arteryalso known as helicine arteries Either the helicine artery of the penis or the helicine artery of the uterus.

neck of talusalso known as talus neck; talar neck The neck of talus is directed forward and medialward, and comprises the constricted portion of the bone between the body and the oval head. Its upper and medial surfaces are rough, for the attachment of ligaments; its lateral surface is concave and is continuous below with the deep groove for the interosseous talocalcaneal ligament.
non-connected functional system An anatomical group whose component structures share a common function.
glandular system A non-connected functional system that is composed primarily of a gland.
lateral structure Any structure that is placed on one side of the left-right axis of a bilaterian.

circulatory organalso known as cardiac pump; heart or heart like organ A hollow, muscular organ, which, by contracting rhythmically, contributes to the circulation of lymph, blood or analogs. Examples: a chambered vertebrate heart; the tubular peristaltic heart of ascidians; the dorsal vessel of an insect; the lymoh heart of a reptile.
nucleus of dorsal thalamusalso known as dorsal thalamic nucleus; nucleus of thalamus proper A nucleus of brain that is part of a dorsal thalamus.
nucleus of ventral thalamusalso known as ventral thalamic nucleus A nucleus of brain that is part of a ventral thalamus.

pineal complex A cluster in the epithalamus that consists of the pineal body and any associated structures, such as the parapineal gland or the parietal organ. The complex is poorly developed in mammals.

saphenous arteryalso known as ramus saphenus (arteria descendentis genus) A branch of the descending genicular artery, the last branch (most distal) of the femoral, the saphenous is also variable. It usually lies between the sartorius and the garcilis muscles and supplies their distal ends. The artery accompanies the saphenous nerve. It usually supplies the skin on the medial and proximal part of the leg. The artery may continue to join, in varying degrees, the dorsalis pedis artery and plantaris pedis arteries.
heart plus pericardiumalso known as heart/pericardium heart plus pericardium

proper hepatic arteryalso known as hepatic artery proper The hepatic artery proper (also proper hepatic artery), arises from the common hepatic artery and runs alongside the portal vein and the common bile duct to form the portal triad. The hepatic artery proper gives off a small supraduodenal artery to the duodenal bulb. Then the right gastric artery comes off and runs to the left along the lesser curvature of the stomach to meet the left gastric artery, which is a branch of the celiac trunk. It subsequently gives off the cystic artery, which feeds the gallbladder, before bifurcating into the right and left hepatic arteries. Of note, the right and left hepatic arteries may demonstrate variant anatomy. A replaced right hepatic artery may arise from the superior mesenteric artery (SMA) and a replaced left hepatic artery may arise from the left gastric artery.
left hepatic arteryalso known as left branch of hepatic artery; left part of hepatic artery proper; ramus sinister (arteria hepatica propria) A hepatic artery that is part of a left lobe of liver.

right hepatic arteryalso known as ramus dexter (arteria hepatica propria); right branch of hepatic artery proper; right part of hepatic artery proper A hepatic artery that is part of a right lobe of liver.

sural nerve The sural nerve (short saphenous nerve), formed by the junction of the medial sural cutaneous with the peroneal anastomotic branch of the lateral sural cutaneous nerve, passes downward near the lateral margin of the tendo calcaneus, lying close to the small saphenous vein, to the interval between the lateral malleolus and the calcaneus. It runs forward below the lateral malleolus, and is continued as the lateral dorsal cutaneous nerve along the lateral side of the foot and little toe (via a dorsal digital nerve), communicating on the dorsum of the foot with the intermediate dorsal cutaneous nerve, a branch of the superficial peroneal. In the leg, its branches communicate with those of the posterior femoral cutaneous.
frontal gyrus A gyrus that is part of a frontal cortex.
sagittal sinus Either the inferior or superior sagittal sinus.
anal canal epitheliumalso known as anal canal epithelium; epithelium of anal canal An epithelium that is part of a anal canal.
heterogeneous tissuealso known as portion of heterogeneous tissue heterogeneous tissue
cranial or facial musclealso known as cranial/facial muscle cranial or facial muscle
liver blood vessel A blood vessel that is part of a liver.
eye epithelium An epithelium that is part of a camera-type eye.
duodenum lamina propriaalso known as duodenal lamina propria; lamina propria mucosae of duodenum; lamina propria of duodenum A lamina propria that is part of a duodenum.
visceral abdominal lymph node visceral abdominal lymph node
pelvic lymph nodealso known as lymph node of pelvis Any lymph node within the abdominal pelvic region.
parietal pelvic lymph node parietal pelvic lymph node

common iliac lymph nodealso known as common iliac node; iliac lymph node The external iliac lymph nodes, from eight to ten in number, lie along the external iliac vessels. They are arranged in three groups, one on the lateral, another on the medial, and a third on the anterior aspect of the vessels; the third group is, however, sometimes absent. Their principal afferents are derived from the inguinal lymph nodes, the deep lymphatics of the abdominal wall below the umbilicus and of the adductor region of the thigh, and the lymphatics from the glans penis vel clitoridis, the membranous urethra, the prostate, the fundus of the urinary bladder, the cervix uteri, and upper part of the vagina.
external iliac lymph nodealso known as external iliac node external iliac lymph node

internal iliac lymph nodealso known as internal iliac node The internal iliac lymph nodes (or hypogastric) surround the internal iliac artery and its branches (the hypogastric vessels), and receive the lymphatics corresponding to the distribution of the branches of it, i. e. , they receive lymphatics from all the pelvic viscera, from the deeper parts of the perineum, including the membranous and cavernous portions of the urethra, and from the buttock and back of the thigh. It does not receive lymph from the ovary, testis, or superior half of the rectum; the gonads drain to the paraaortic lymph nodes, while the superior half of the rectum drains to the pararectal lymph nodes.
ileocolic lymph nodealso known as nodi lymphoidei ileocolici One of the lymph nodes that form a chain around the ileocolic artery.

paraaortic lymph nodealso known as lateral aortic lymph node; lateral aortic node; para-aortic lymph node The paraaortic lymph nodes (also known as para-aortic, periaortic, and peri-aortic) are a group of lymph nodes that lie in front of the lumbar vertebral bodies near the aorta. These lymph nodes receive drainage from the lower gastrointestinal tract and the pelvic organs.
lymph node of lower limb A lymph node that is part of a hindlimb.
mesocolic lymph node mesocolic lymph node
pulmonary capillaryalso known as capillary of lung A capillary that is part of a lung.

palmar branch of median nervealso known as ramus palmaris (nervus medianus); median nerve palmar branch; palmar branch of anterior interosseous nerve; palmar cutaneous branch of median nerve; ramus palmaris nervus interossei antebrachii anterior The palmar branch of the median nerve is a branch of the median nerve which arises at the lower part of the forearm and innervates skin of proximal central palm and thenar eminence.

zygomatic process of maxillaalso known as malar process of maxilla; processus zygomaticus (maxilla); processus zygomaticus maxillae; zygomaticoorbital process of maxilla The zygomatic process of the maxilla (malar process) is a rough triangular eminence, situated at the angle of separation of the anterior, zygomatic, and orbital surfaces. In front it forms part of the anterior surface. Behind it is concave, and forms part of the infratemporal fossa. Above it is rough and serrated for articulation with the zygomatic bone. Below it presents the prominent arched border which marks the division between the anterior and infratemporal surfaces.
liver stromaalso known as hepatic stroma; stroma of liver A stroma that is part of a liver.

capsule of liveralso known as tunica fibrosa hepatis; capsula fibrosa perivascularis; fibrous capsule of liver; glisson's capsule; hepatic capsule; tunica fibrosa (hepar) A collagenous capsule covering the external surface of the liver.

foramen spinosum of sphenoid bonealso known as foramen spinosum A foramen in the sphenoid bone through which the middle meningeal artery, middle meningeal vein, and the meningeal branch of the mandibular nerve pass.

palmaris longus musclealso known as musculus palmaris longus; palmaris longus The palmaris longus is seen as a small tendon between the flexor carpi radialis and the flexor carpi ulnaris, although it is not always present. The muscle is absent in about 14 percent of the population, however this varies greatly with ethnicity. Absence of palmaris does not have any known effect on grip strength. Palmaris longus can be palpated by touching the pads of the fifth and first fingers and flexing the wrist. The tendon, if present, will be very visible.
muscularis mucosa of fundus of urinary bladder A muscularis mucosa that is part of a fundus of urinary bladder.
pelvic ganglionalso known as inferior hypogastric ganglion pelvic ganglion
muscularis mucosae of jejunum A muscularis mucosa that is part of a jejunum.

frontal lobealso known as lobus frontalis; lobi frontales Frontal lobe is the anterior-most of five lobes of the cerebral hemisphere. It is bounded by the central sulcus on its posterior border and by the longitudinal cerebral fissure on its medial border.

lobe of cerebral hemispherealso known as cerebral hemisphere lobe; cerebral lobe; lobe of cerebral cortex; lobe parts of cerebral cortex; lobi cerebri Subdivision of telencephalon which is one of a number of subdivisions of each hemisphere separated by both real landmarks (sulci and fissures) and arbitrary boundaries[FMA,modified].
cortex of cerebral lobealso known as cortex of cerebral hemisphere lobe; cortex of lobe of cerebral hemisphere Grey matter neocortex region of a lobe of the cerebral hemisphere.
limbic cortexalso known as cortex of limbic lobe; limbic lobe cortex limbic cortex

central nervous system gray matter layeralso known as CNS gray matter layer; CNS grey matter layer; gray matter layer of neuraxis; grey matter layer of neuraxis A layer of of the central nervous system that is part of gray matter.
spinal cord column spinal cord column
subdivision of spinal cord ventral column subdivision of spinal cord ventral column
white matter of midbrainalso known as mesencephalic white matter A white matter that is part of the midbrain.
superficial cerebral veinalso known as cortical cerebral vein The superficial cerebral veins are a group of veins in the head. This group includes the superior cerebral veins.
deep cerebral vein The deep cerebral veins are a group of veins in the head. This group includes the superior thalamostriate vein.
pit An roughly circular indentation in a surface.
lamina of gray matter of spinal cordalso known as rexed lamina lamina of gray matter of spinal cord
isthmus of fallopian tubealso known as isthmus tubae uterinae isthmus of fallopian tube

entire extraembryonic componentalso known as extra-embryonic component; extraembryonic component The part of the conceptus that may be lost before birth or will be discarded at birth, or when the embryo becomes an independent organism.
extensor pollicis brevis musclealso known as extensor pollicis brevis The Extensor pollicis brevis lies on the medial side of, and is closely connected with, the Abductor pollicis longus.
paired venous dural sinusalso known as paired dural venous sinus paired venous dural sinus
marginal venous sinusalso known as intracranial marginal sinus A paired dural venous sinus at the rim of the foramen magnum.
unpaired venous dural sinusalso known as unpaired dural venous sinus unpaired venous dural sinus

meningeal branch of spinal nervealso known as ramus meningeus nervorum spinales; recurrent meningeal branch of spinal nerve; sinuvertebral branch of spinal nerve Branch of spinal nerve that innervates the structures of the vertebral column.

communicating branch of spinal nerve Rami communicans (plural rami communicantes) is the term used for a nerve which connects two other nerves. When used without further definition, it almost always refers to a communicating branch between a spinal nerve and the sympathetic trunk. More specifically, it usually refers to one of the following: Gray ramus communicans White ramus communicans.
abdominal visceraalso known as abdominal viscera; abdominal viscera set; set of abdominal viscera A viscus that is part of a abdomen.
proximal mesopodial endochondral element A mesopodial endochondral element that is in the most proximal part of the mesopodial skeleton, connected to the zeugopodial skeleton.

distal mesopodial endochondral elementalso known as distal mesopodial An endochondral element in the distal portion of the mesopodial skeleton, between the central mesopodial skeleton and the metapodial skeleton.
distal mesopodial bone A distal mesopodial endochondral element that is composed primarily of a bone tissue.
mammary lobe A cluster of mammary gland lobules. In humans this is a distinct lobe and located in the breast region.

caudal vertebra endochondral elementalso known as caudal vertebra element; tail vertebra element Any vertebra endochondral element that is part of the caudal region of the vertebral column (tail or coccyx).
pulmonary lymphatic vesselalso known as lymphatic vessel of lung A lymphatic vessel that is part of a lung.

labyrinthine arteryalso known as arteria auditiva interna; arteria labyrinthi; internal auditory artery A long slender branch of the anterior inferior cerebellar artery (85%-100% cases) or basilar artery (<15% cases), arises from near the middle of the artery; it accompanies the vestibulocochlear nerve through the internal acoustic meatus, and is distributed to the internal ear.
stroma of pancreasalso known as pancreatic stroma A stroma that is part of a pancreas.
thymic arteryalso known as thymic branch of internal thoracic artery A vein that supplies blood to the thymus.
thyroid vein A vein that drains a thyroid gland.
internal pudendal veinalso known as vena pudenda interna Accompanying vein of internal pudendal artery.
external pudendal veinalso known as vena pudenda externa One of the veins of the pelvis which drain into the great saphenous vein.
skeletal musculature skeletal musculature
jejunal artery A branch of the superior mesenteric artery that supplies the jejunum.
lacrimal vein A vein that drains a lacrimal gland.
submucosa of digestive tract Any portion of submucosa that lines the digestive tract.
layer of muscle tissue Any organ component layer that consists of muscle tissue.
muscular coat of digestive tractalso known as tunica muscularis of digestive tract A muscular coat that is part of a digestive tract.

posterior superior alveolar arteryalso known as superior posterior alveolar artery The posterior superior alveolar artery (posterior dental artery) is given off from the maxillary, frequently in conjunction with the infraorbital just as the trunk of the vessel is passing into the pterygopalatine fossa.

vidian nervealso known as nerve of pterygoid canal; pterygoid canal nerve; vidian nerve A nerve that is formed by the junction of the great petrosal nerve and the deep petrosal nerve and continues on to innervate the palate, nose and lacrimal gland.
trigeminal nerve musclealso known as muscle innervated by the trigeminal nerve; muscles innervated by the trigeminal nerve Muscle innervated by the trigeminal nerve (Cranial Nerve V).
cardiac muscle tissue of ventriclealso known as ventricular cardiac muscle tissue; ventricular heart muscle cardiac muscle tissue of ventricle
neck of bone elementalso known as bone neck; neck of bone The neck region of a bone organ.
neck of fibulaalso known as fibula neck; fibular neck neck of fibula
heart vasculaturealso known as cardiac vasculature An interconnected tubular multi-tissue structure that contains fluid that is actively transported around the heart.

pelvic splanchnic nervealso known as pelvic splanchnic parasympathetic nerve A splanchnic nerves that arises from sacral spinal nerves S2, S3, S4 to provide parasympathetic innervation to the hindgut.

thoracic splanchnic nerve Thoracic splanchnic nerves are splanchnic nerves that arise from the sympathetic trunk in the thorax and travel inferiorly to provide sympathetic innervation to the abdomen. The nerves contain preganglionic sympathetic and general visceral afferent fibers.
greater splanchnic nervealso known as greater thoracic splanchnic nerve greater splanchnic nerve
lesser splanchnic nervealso known as lesser thoracic splanchnic nerve lesser splanchnic nerve

lumbar splanchnic nerve The lumbar splanchnic nerves are splanchnic nerves that arise from the lumbar part of the sympathetic trunk and travel to an adjacent plexus near the aorta. They are originated from L1 and L2. These nerves contain preganglionic sympathetic and visceral afferent fibers. The site of synapse is found in the prevertebral ganglia and innervate the smooth muscle and glands of the pelvic viscera and hindgut.
bladder organ A membranous sac in animals that serves as the receptacle of a liquid or contains gas.
reproductive system mucosaalso known as genital mucosa reproductive system mucosa
gemellus muscle One of the two small muscular fasciculi, accessories to the tendon of the Obturator internus which is received into a groove between them.

inferior gemellus musclealso known as gemellus inferior; inferior gemellus; musculus gemellus inferior Gemellus muscle that arises from the upper part of the tuberosity of the ischium, immediately below the groove for the Obturator internus tendon. It blends with the lower part of the tendon of the Obturator internus, and is inserted with it into the medial surface of the greater trochanter.

superior gemellus musclealso known as gemellus superior; musculus gemellus superior; superior gemellus The smaller of the two gemellus muscles that arises from the outer surface of the spine of the ischium, blends with the upper part of the tendon of the Obturator internus, and is inserted with it into the medial surface of the greater trochanter[WP].
white matter of hindbrain A white matter that is part of the hindbrain.
white matter of forebrain A white matter that is part of the forebrain.
white matter of myelencephalonalso known as myelencephalic white matter A white matter that is part of the myelencephalon.
gray matter of hindbrainalso known as gray matter of the hindbrain gray matter of hindbrain
gray matter of forebrain gray matter of forebrain
gray matter of midbrain gray matter of midbrain
gray matter of diencephalon gray matter of diencephalon
inferior rostral gyrus inferior rostral gyrus
superior rostral gyrusalso known as superior rostral gyrus superior rostral gyrus
rostral gyrus rostral gyrus
white matter of metencephalon white matter of metencephalon
white matter of pons white matter of pons
commissure of telencephalonalso known as telencephalic commissures commissure of telencephalon
sensory organ epithelium sensory organ epithelium
exocrine gland of integumental systemalso known as integumental exocrine gland; integumental system exocrine gland An exocrine gland that is part of a integumental system.
forebrain ipsilateral fiber tracts forebrain ipsilateral fiber tracts
white matter radiationalso known as neuraxis radiation; radiation of neuraxis white matter radiation
radiation of cerebral hemispherealso known as cerebral hemisphere radiation radiation of cerebral hemisphere

optic radiationalso known as Gratiolet's radiation The optic radiation (also known as the geniculo-calcarine tract or as the geniculostriate pathway) is a collection of axons from relay neurons in the lateral geniculate nucleus of the thalamus carrying visual information to the visual cortex (also called striate cortex) along the calcarine fissure. There is one such tract on each side of the brain.

planum temporale The planum temporale is the cortical area just posterior to the auditory cortex within the Sylvian fissure. It is a triangular region which forms the heart of Wernicke's area, one of the most important functional areas for language. The planum temporale shows a significant asymmetry. In 65% of all individuals the left planum temporale appears to be more developed, while the right planum temporale is more developed in only 10%. In some peoplebs brains, the planum temporale is more than five times larger on the left than on the right, making it the most asymmetrical structure in the brain. This greater size of the left planum temporale compared with the right is already present in the foetus, where it can be observed starting from the 31st week of gestation. This observation strengthens the hypothesis of a genetic predisposition for brain asymmetry.
colic flexurealso known as flexura coli A sharp bend between consecutive segments of the colon.

splenic flexure of colonalso known as flexura coli splenica; left colic flexure; splenic flexure; splenic flexure of colon The splenic (or left colic) flexure is a sharp bend between the transverse and the descending colon in the left upper quadrant of humans. The left colic flexure is near the spleen, and hence called the splenic flexure. There are two colic flexures in the transverse colon — the other being the hepatic flexure in the right upper quadrant.

hepatic flexure of colonalso known as flexura coli heaptica; hepatic flexure; hepatic flexure of colon; right colic flexure Hepatic (or the right colic) flexure is the sharp bend between the ascending and the transverse colon. The right colic flexure is adjacent to the liver, and is therefore also known as the hepatic flexure. Thus, the left colic flexure is also known as the splenic flexure (as it is close to the spleen). The hepatic flexure lies in the right upper quadrant of the abdomen in humans.
epithelium of crypt of Lieberkuhn of large intestine epithelium of crypt of Lieberkuhn of large intestine
splenic arteriole splenic arteriole
nasociliary nervealso known as nasal nerve A branch of the ophthalmic nerve that serves to supply the mucous membrane of the nose, the tip of the nose, and the conjunctiva.
long ciliary nerve A branch of the nasociliary nerve that innervates the ciliary muscles, the iris, and the cornea.
short ciliary nervealso known as lower branch of ciliary ganglion A branch of the ciliary ganglion that innervates the ciliary muscles, the iris, and the tunics of the eyeball.
nervous system cell part layer Single layer of a laminar structure, identified by different density, arrangement or size of cells and processes arranged in flattened layers or lamina[CUMBO].
visceral serous membranealso known as visceral wall of serous membrane Serous membrane layer that is adjacent to and lines an organ.
basal layer of endometriumalso known as pars basalis of endometrium; stratum basalis of endometrium The layer of endometrial epithelium adjacent to the uterine cavity.
outer layer of endometriumalso known as functional layer of endometrium; stratum functionalis of endometrium The layer of endometrial epithelium adjacent to the myometrium.
placenta blood vessel A blood vessel of the placenta.
occipital fusiform gyrusalso known as occipital fusiform gyrus (OF); occipitotemporal (fusiform) gyrus, occipital part occipital fusiform gyrus
anterior parahippocampal gyrusalso known as parahippocampal gyrus, anterior division The part of the parahippocampal gyrus that includes the perirhinal and entorhinal cortices.
paracingulate gyrusalso known as paracingulate gyrus (PAC) paracingulate gyrus
composite part spanning multiple base regional parts of brainalso known as composite part spanning multiple base regional parts of brain composite part spanning multiple base regional parts of brain
subicular complexalso known as subicular complex A composite structure of the temporal lobe that includes the subiculum, the presubiculum and the parasubicular area (Amaral-90).
planum polarealso known as planum polare A portion of the superior temporal gyrus near the temporal pole in the human.

tegmentumalso known as tegmentum The ventral topographic division of the midbrain; the dorsal topographic division is the tectum. Meckel (1817; see English translation, 1832, vol. 2, p. 467) apparently introduced the term and roughly its definition here for macrodissected adult humans, except he excluded the cerebral peduncle (Tarin, 1753), a white matter tract at the base of the midbrain, which is still common today but is included here. As defined here, tegmentum refers to the whole of the midbrain (Baer, 1837) excluding the tectum but including the pretectal region (Scalia, 1972); see Swanson (2000, pp. 522, 526). Usage of this term is very complex, inconsistent, and illogical; see for example Crosby et al. (1962, pp. 221, 260, 262), Carpenter (1976, p. 367 ff.).
sacral spinal cord white matteralso known as sacral spinal cord white matter sacral spinal cord white matter
thoracic spinal cord gray commissurealso known as thoracic spinal cord gray commissure thoracic spinal cord gray commissure
lumbar spinal cord white matteralso known as lumbar spinal cord white matter lumbar spinal cord white matter
paravermis lobule areaalso known as paravermis of cerebellum; regional parts of the paravermal lobules paravermis lobule area
sacral spinal cord gray matteralso known as sacral spinal cord gray matter sacral spinal cord gray matter
sacral spinal cord lateral hornalso known as sacral spinal cord lateral horn sacral spinal cord lateral horn
cervical spinal cord gray commissurealso known as cervical spinal cord gray commissure cervical spinal cord gray commissure
lumbar spinal cord gray matteralso known as lumbar spinal cord gray matter lumbar spinal cord gray matter
lumbar spinal cord ventral hornalso known as lumbar spinal cord ventral horn lumbar spinal cord ventral horn
sacral spinal cord gray commissurealso known as sacral spinal cord gray commissure sacral spinal cord gray commissure
lumbar spinal cord lateral hornalso known as lumbar spinal cord lateral horn lumbar spinal cord lateral horn
sacral spinal cord ventral hornalso known as sacral spinal cord ventral horn sacral spinal cord ventral horn
lumbar spinal cord gray commissurealso known as lumbar spinal cord gray commissure lumbar spinal cord gray commissure
sacral spinal cord dorsal hornalso known as sacral spinal cord dorsal horn sacral spinal cord dorsal horn
amygdalohippocampal area A cytoarchitecturally defined portion of the periamygdalar area and the cortical amygdalar nucleus at the caudal extreme of the amygdala.
vocal organ Any organ that is the primary organ of vocalization behavior. Examples: The laryngeal vocal cord (humans), the syrinx (birds).

cremasteric arteryalso known as cremasteric part of inferior epigastric artery The cremasteric artery (external spermatic artery) is a branch of the Inferior epigastric artery which accompanies the spermatic cord, and supplies the Cremaster and other coverings of the cord, anastomosing with the testicular artery (internal spermatic artery in older texts). (In the female, the cremesteric artery is very small and accompanies the round ligament.).

cranial neuron projection bundle Any of the cranial nerves, or their central nervous system analogs (the optic tract, the epiphyseal tract). These analogs are not true nerves, and are instead evaginated sensory afferents emanating from the brain.
vestibular bulb arteryalso known as arteria bulbi vestibuli; artery of bulb of vestibule The artery of bulb of vestibule is a branch of the internal pudendal artery.

autonomic nervealso known as nervus visceralis; visceral nerve The autonomic nerve is a small nerve which carries postganglionic sympathetic and parasympathetic neurons from the zygomaticotemporal nerve; a branch of the maxillary nerve, to the lacrimal nerve; a branch of the ophthalmic nerve. These neurons derive from the superior cervical ganglion and the pterygopalatine ganglion respectively. They will travel to the lacrimal gland via the lacrimal nerve. Parasympathetic will induce lacrimation and vice versa.
sympathetic nerve sympathetic nerve
morphological feature A part of an organism or organ that is continuous with its surroundings and distinguished from its surroundings based on morphology.
lymphomyeloid tissue lymphomyeloid tissue

uncus of parahippocampal gyrusalso known as uncus hippocampi The anterior extremity of the Parahippocampal gyrus is recurved in the form of a hook, the uncus, which is separated from the apex of the temporal lobe by a slight fissure, the incisura temporalis. Although superficially continuous with the hippocampal gyrus, the uncus forms morphologically a part of the rhinencephalon. The term uncus was coined by Felix Vicq dbAzyr (1748b1794).
juxtaglomerular arteriole juxtaglomerular arteriole
insular cortexalso known as cortex of insula; insular neocortex insular cortex

scapular muscle Any of the muscles that are responsible for moving the scapula. In humans these are the levator scapulae, the infraspinatus muscle, the teres major, the teres minor, and the supraspinatus muscle.
multi organ part structure An multicellular anatomical structure that has subparts of multiple organs as a part.
cell cluster A cluster of cells, largely surrounded by a morphological boundary.
disconnected anatomical group Material anatomical entity consisting of multiple anatomical structures that are not connected to each other.
anatomical collection A collection of anatomical structures that are alike in terms of their morphology or developmental origin.

arcuate artery of foot The arcuate artery of the foot (metatarsal artery) arises a little anterior to the lateral tarsal artery; it passes lateralward, over the bases of the metatarsal bones, beneath the tendons of the Extensor digitorum brevis, its direction being influenced by its point of origin; and its anastomoses with the lateral tarsal and lateral plantar arteries. This vessel gives off the second, third, and fourth dorsal metatarsal arteries. It is not present in all individuals.
layer of smooth muscle tissue Any organ component layer that consists of smooth muscle tissue.
zone of organalso known as organ sector; organ zonal region; organ zone zone of organ

superficial epigastric artery An artery that arises from the femoral artery and supplies the abdominal wall. It distributes branches to the superficial subinguinal lymph glands, the superficial fascia, and the integument; it anastomoses with branches of the inferior epigastric, and with its fellow of the opposite side.

middle thyroid vein The middle thyroid vein collects the blood from the lower part of the thyroid gland, and after being joined by some veins from the larynx and trachea, ends in the lower part of the internal jugular vein.
jugular bulbalso known as bulb of jugular vein jugular bulb
superior bulb of internal jugular veinalso known as bulbus superior venae jugularis; superior bulb of jugular vein superior bulb of internal jugular vein
inferior bulb of internal jugular veinalso known as inferior bulb of jugular vein; bulbus inferior venae jugularis inferior bulb of internal jugular vein

sacral nerve plexusalso known as plexus sacralis; sacral plexus A nerve plexus which provides motor and sensory nerves for the posterior thigh, most of the lower leg, the entire foot, and part of the pelvis.
lumbar nerve plexusalso known as lumbar plexus; plexus lumbalis A nervous plexus in the lumbar region of the body which forms part of the lumbosacral plexus.
anterior cortical amygdaloid nucleus anterior cortical amygdaloid nucleus
outer renal medulla loop of Henlealso known as loop of Henle, outer medullary portion outer renal medulla loop of Henle
renal medulla loop of Henlealso known as loop of Henle of renal medulla; loop of Henle, medullary portion renal medulla loop of Henle
central gray substancealso known as substantia grisea centralis; central grey substance central gray substance
abdominal oblique musclealso known as oblique abdominal muscle Either the external or internal abdominal oblique muscles.
rectal arteryalso known as hemorrhoidal artery rectal artery
superior rectal arteryalso known as superior hemorrhoidal artery The superior rectal artery (superior hemorrhoidal artery) is an artery that descends into the pelvis to supply blood to the rectum.

middle temporal artery The middle temporal artery arises immediately above the zygomatic arch, and, perforating the temporal fascia, gives branches to the Temporalis, anastomosing with the deep temporal branches of the internal maxillary. It occasionally gives off a zygomaticoC6rbital branch, which runs along the upper border of the zygomatic arch, between the two layers of the temporal fascia, to the lateral angle of the orbit.
excretory duct excretory duct
intrinsic muscle Any of the muscles that are entirely within the body part or segment moved by them.
auditory ossicle endochondral elementalso known as auditory skeletal element; middle ear ossicle element auditory ossicle endochondral element
anterior nasal spine of maxillaalso known as spina nasalis anterior corporis maxillae A pointed projection at the front extremity of the intermaxillary suture.

superior cerebral vein The Superior Cerebral Veins, eight to twelve in number, drain the superior, lateral, and medial surfaces of the hemispheres, and are mainly lodged in the sulci between the gyri, but some run across the gyri. They open into the superior sagittal sinus; the anterior veins runs nearly at right angles to the sinus; the posterior and larger veins are directed obliquely forward and open into the sinus in a direction more or less opposed to the current of the blood contained within it.

internal cerebral vein The internal cerebral veins (veins of Galen; deep cerebral veins) drain the deep parts of the hemisphere and are two in number; each is formed near the interventricular foramen by the union of the terminal and choroid veins. They run backward parallel with one another, between the layers of the tela chorioidea of the third ventricle, and beneath the splenium of the corpus callosum, where they unite to form a short trunk, the great cerebral vein; just before their union each receives the corresponding basal vein.

sigmoid arteryalso known as inferior left colic artery The sigmoid arteries, two or three in number, run obliquely downward and to the left behind the peritoneum and in front of the Psoas major, ureter, and internal spermatic vessels. Their branches supply the lower part of the descending colon, the iliac colon, and the sigmoid or pelvic colon; anastomosing above with the left colic, and below with the superior hemorrhoidal artery.

calcarine arteryalso known as calcarine branch of medial occipital artery; ramus calcarinus (arteria occipitalis medialis) An artery that branches from the medial occipital artery that aligns with the calcarine sulcus.
posterior parietal artery posterior parietal artery
anterior temporal artery A branch of the middle cerebral artery that supplies blood to the anterior part of the temporal lobe.

superficial middle cerebral veinalso known as Sylvian vein; vein of Labbe A vein that runs along the fissure of Sylvius to the cavernous sinus on the lateral surface of the brain and connects to the superior sagittal and transverse sinuses.
medial circumflex femoral vein A circumflex femoral vein that accompanies the medial circumflex femoral artery.
posterior external jugular vein A vein that drains the superficial muscles and integument of the upper back portion of the neck into the external jugular vein.
left subcostal veinalso known as vena subcostalis sinistra A vein that extends along the bottom of the twelfth rib on the left side of the body.
posterior temporal artery posterior temporal artery

superior thoracic artery The superior thoracic artery (highest thoracic artery) is a small vessel normally arising from the first division of the axillary artery, but may arise from the thoracoacromial artery, itself a branch of the second division of the axillary artery. Running forward and medialward along the upper border of the pectoralis minor, the superior thoracic artery passes between it and the pectoralis major to the side of the chest. It supplies branches to the first and second intercostal spaces as well as to the superior portion of serratus anterior. It anastomoses with the internal mammary and intercostal arteries.
supraclavicular lymph nodealso known as nodus lymphaticus supraclavicularis axillae; supraclavicular node A lymph node which is located above the clavicle.
branch of posterior tibial arteryalso known as posterior tibial arterial branch branch of posterior tibial artery
branch of vertebral arteryalso known as vertebral arterial branch branch of vertebral artery
right common iliac arteryalso known as trunk of right common iliac arterial tree right common iliac artery
base of prostatealso known as base of prostate gland; prostatic base The uppermost part of the prostate gland adjacent to the bladder wall.
branch of middle cerebral arteryalso known as middle cerebral arterial branch branch of middle cerebral artery
small cardiac veinalso known as right cardiac vein A vein running parallel to the right coronary artery in the coronary sulcus that drains into the right extremity of the coronary sinus.

branch of anterior cerebral arteryalso known as anterior cerebral arterial branch An arterial branch arising from the anterior cerebral artery. It includes the callosomarginal artery, frontopolar artery, medial orbitofrontal artery, pericallosal artery, and recurrent artery of Heubner.
cystic veinalso known as cholecystic vein A blood vessel carrying deoxygenated blood from the gallbladder and the cystic duct into the right branch of the portal vein.
branch of left coronary arteryalso known as left coronary arterial branch branch of left coronary artery
branch of external carotid arteryalso known as external carotid arterial subdivision; subdivision of external carotid artery branch of external carotid artery
hypophysial artery An artery that supplies the pituitary gland.

superior hypophysial arteryalso known as superior hypophyseal artery The superior hypophysial artery is an artery supplying the pars tuberalis,the infundibulum of the pituitary gland and the median eminence. It is a branch of the posterior communicating artery which branches from the internal carotid artery in the circle of Willis..

circumflex branch of left coronary arteryalso known as circumflex coronary artery; left circumflex branch of left coronary artery; ramus circumflexus (arteria coronaria sinistra) Branch of left coronary artery which runs perpendicular to the anterior interventricular branch of the left coronary artery on the left side of the interventricular sulcus and supplies the left side of the heart.
postcapillary venule postcapillary venule
right suprarenal veinalso known as vena suprarenalis (adrenalis) dextra A vein that drains blood from the right adrenal gland into the inferior vena cava.
apex of prostatealso known as apex of prostate gland; prostatic apex The lowest part of the prostate gland adjacent to the superior fascia of the urogenital diaphragm.
triangular ligament of liver triangular ligament of liver
anterior parietal artery The artery that delivers blood to the anterior portion of the parietal lobe.
right subcostal veinalso known as vena subcostalis dextra A vein that extends along the bottom of the twelfth rib on the right side of the body.
left suprarenal vein A vein that drains blood from the left adrenal gland into the left renal artery.
branch of basilar arteryalso known as basilar arterial branch branch of basilar artery

inferior hypophysial arteryalso known as inferior hypophyseal artery The inferior hypophysial artery is an artery supplying the pituitary gland. It is a branch of the cavernous carotid artery (internal carotid artery).
hilum of lymph nodealso known as hilum nodi lymphoidei; lymph node hilum The concave side of the lymph node.
left common iliac arteryalso known as trunk of left common iliac arterial tree left common iliac artery

basal veinalso known as basal vein of rosenthal; rosenthal's vein The basal vein is formed at the anterior perforated substance by the union of (a) a small anterior cerebral vein which accompanies the anterior cerebral artery and supplies the medial surface of the frontal lobe by the fronto-basal vein. (b) the deep middle cerebral vein (deep Sylvian vein), which receives tributaries from the insula and neighboring gyri, and runs in the lower part of the lateral cerebral fissure, and (c) the inferior striate veins, which leave the corpus striatum through the anterior perforated substance. The basal vein passes backward around the cerebral peduncle, and ends in the internal cerebral vein; it receives tributaries from the interpeduncular fossa, the inferior horn of the lateral ventricle, the hippocampal gyrus, and the mid-brain.
deep middle cerebral vein The blood vessel that receives deoxygenated blood from the insula and gyri and drains into the basal vein of Rosenthal deep in the lateral sulcus.
esophageal arteryalso known as aortic esophageal artery; oesophageal artery Any of several arteries that arise from the aorta and supply blood to the esophagus.
uveal veinalso known as ciliary vein uveal vein

posterior ciliary veinalso known as vorticose vein The outer layer of the choroid (lamina vasculosa) consists, in part, of the larger branches of the short ciliary arteries which run forward between the veins, before they bend inward to end in the capillaries, but is formed principally of veins, named, from their arrangement, the vorticose veins. They converge to four or five equidistant trunks, which pierce the sclera about midway between the sclero-corneal junction and the entrance of the optic nerve. They drain uveal tract.
colic artery colic artery

vasculature of integumentalso known as superficial part of circulatory system; superficial vasculature The part of the circulatory system that lies within the subcutaneous tissue layers close to the surface of the skin.
superficial vein Any of the veins carrying deoxygenated blood from the subcutaneous tissue layers.
deep vein A blood vessel carrying deoxygenated blood far beneath the skin usually accompanying an artery.
left cardiac chamber Any chamber of the left side of the heart.
right cardiac chamber Any chamber of the right side of the heart.

nasal turbinalalso known as nasal turbinal; nasal turbinal element; nasal turbinate; turbinal; turbinate A skeletal element of the ethmoid region with complex morphology that are lined with mucuous membranes involved in either olfaction or air conditioning.
middle vesical artery The middle vesical artery, usually a branch of the superior vesical artery, is distributed to the fundus of the bladder and the seminal vesicles.
laryngeal nerve Any nerve that innervates the larynx.
nerve innervating pinnaalso known as auricular nerve Any nerve that innervates the pinna.
nerve of clitorisalso known as clitoral nerve; clitoris nerve Any nerve that innervates the clitoris.

paraumbilical veinalso known as venae paraumbilicales The small superficial veins that arise from the cutaneous veins, and run from the umbilicus along the round ligament of the liver; these terminate as accessory portal veins in the liver.
deep facial vein The anterior facial vein receives a branch of considerable size, the deep facial vein, from the pterygoid venous plexus.
parotid veinalso known as anterior parotid vein; parotid branch of facial vein parotid vein
intrapulmonary bronchus intrapulmonary bronchus
coccygeal nerve plexusalso known as coccygeal plexus; plexus coccygeus The coccygeal plexus is a plexus of nerves near the coccyx bone.
mesenteric ganglion mesenteric ganglion

inferior mesenteric nerve plexusalso known as plexus nervosus mesentericus inferior; inferior mesenteric plexus; plexus mesentericus inferior The inferior mesenteric plexus is derived chiefly from the aortic plexus. It surrounds the inferior mesenteric artery, and divides into a number of secondary plexuses, which are distributed to all the parts supplied by the artery, viz. , the left colic and sigmoid plexuses, which supply the descending and sigmoid parts of the colon; and the superior hemorrhoidal plexus, which supplies the rectum and joins in the pelvis with branches from the pelvic plexuses.
mesenteric plexus mesenteric plexus
aortic plexus aortic plexus
ganglion of ciliary nerve Any parasympathetic ganglion that extends fibers into the short ciliary nerve. Includes both the main and acccessory ciliary ganglia.
peritoneal sac A serous sac that is the aggregate of the peritoneum and the peritoneal cavity, located in the abdominal cavity.

right gastroepiploic arteryalso known as arteria gastro-omentalis dextra; arteria gastroepiploica dextra; arteria gastroomentalis dextra; right gastro-epiploic artery; right gastro-omental artery; right gastroomental artery Artery that runs from right to left along the greater curvature of the stomach, between the layers of the greater omentum, anastomosing with the left gastroepiploic branch of the splenic artery.

left gastroepiploic arteryalso known as arteria gastro-omentalis sinistra; arteria gastroepiploica sinistra; arteria gastroomentalis sinistra; left gastro-epiploic artery; left gastro-omental artery; left gastroomental artery; left inferior gastric artery Artery that runs from left to right along the greater curvature of the stomach, between the layers of the greater omentum, and anastomoses with the right gastroepiploic.
anterior segment of paracentral lobulealso known as anterior part of paracentral lobule; medial segment of precentral gyrus; paracentral lobule, anterior part anterior segment of paracentral lobule

paracentral lobulealso known as lobulus paracentralis The junction of the precentral gyrus and postcentral gyrus on the medial surface of the cerebral cortex. It lies across the boundary between the frontal lobe and the parietal lobe.
posterior segment of paracentral lobulealso known as posterior part of paracentral lobule posterior segment of paracentral lobule
scleral lamina cribrosaalso known as lamina cribrosa of sclera; lamina cribrosa sclerae The perforated part of the sclera through which pass the axons of the retinal ganglion cells.

vein of vestibular aqueductalso known as vena aqueductus vestibuli; vestibular aqueduct vein A vein that leaves the vestibule through an individual bone canal running parallel to the vestibular aqueduct up to the dura of the posterior side of the petrosa in the area of the endolymphatic sac. It then opens in the inferior petrosal sinus or the jugular bulb. The vein receives other branches from the bone, dura and sac.
skin appendage folliclealso known as cutaneous appendage follicle; skin follicle An organ subunit in the skin that gives rise to cutaneous appendage.

palmaris brevisalso known as musculus palmaris brevis; palmaris brevis muscle The Palmaris brevis is a thin, quadrilateral muscle, placed beneath the integument of the ulnar side of the hand. It arises by tendinous fasciculi from the transverse carpal ligament and palmar aponeurosis; the fleshy fibers are inserted into the skin on the ulnar border of the palm of the hand. The muscle is innervated by the superficial branch of the ulnar nerve, containing fibers from the eighth cervical and first thoracic nerves.
anatomical surface region Material anatomical entity that forms the outermost boundary of an anatomical structure.
tympanic nerve The tympanic nerve (nerve of Jacobson) is a branch of the glossopharyngeal nerve found near the ear.
respiratory system gland Any gland that is part os the respiratory system.
penis blood vessel penis blood vessel

renal pelvis/ureteralso known as renal pelvis and ureter; renal pelvis plus ureter The upper tract of the renal system. The renal pelvis is the large cavity in the middle of each kidney. Urine drains from each kidney through a long tube called the ureter, into the bladder, where it is stored until it is passed from the body through the urethra.
tributary of central retinal veinalso known as central retinal venous tributary tributary of central retinal vein
vasculature of central nervous system plus retina vasculature of central nervous system plus retina
anatomical border An anatomical structure that is located along the line dividing two regions of an anatomical structure.
wall of left ureteralso known as left ureteral wall wall of left ureter
intestinal lymph nodealso known as intestinal node; visceral lumbar lymph node intestinal lymph node
colic lymph nodealso known as colic node; pericolic lymph node; pericolonic lymph node colic lymph node
cystic arteryalso known as cholecystic artery An artery that supplies oxygenated blood to the cystic duct.
dorsal vein of penis One of the superficial dorsal vein of the penis or the deep dorsal vein of the penis.

spleen pulpalso known as Malpighian corpuscles; pulp of spleen; splenic pulp The parenchyma of the spleen, consisting of lymphocytes and macrophages. It lies between the splenic trabecula. Red pulp is the part suffused with blood and white pulp consists of areas of lymphatic tissue where there are sleeves of lymphocytes and macrophages.
parenchyma of spleenalso known as splenic parenchyma A parenchyma that is part of a spleen.
digestive tract junction An anatomical junction between two parts of the digestive tract.
postovulatory follicle postovulatory follicle

fenestrated capillaryalso known as fenestrated capillary vessel Capillary that has pores in the endothelial cells (60-80 nm in diameter) that are spanned by a diaphragm of radially oriented fibrils and allow small molecules and limited amounts of protein to diffuse.
extrapancreatic duct Portion of the pancreatic duct, external to the pancreas body that connects the pancreas with the hepatopancreatic ampulla.
external integument structure Structures of the dermis, epidermis, glands and pigment cells recognizable on the external surfaces of the integument.
limb external integument structure Dermal, epidermal, glandular and pigment structures of the limb integument.
skeletal element projection Anatomical projection that is composed of bone or cartilage tissue.

digit plus metapodial segmentalso known as digit digitopodial subdivision; digit ray A subdivision of the autopod consisting of digit plus the region incorporating a single metapodial element. These segments are typically repeated along the pre-axiom to post-axial axis.
obsolete distal-most point of medial condyle of femur OBSOLETE The distal-most point of the medial condyle of a femur.
duodeno-jejunal junctionalso known as duodeno-jejunal flexure; duodenojejunal flexure; duodenojejunal junction; flexura duodenojejunalis The anatomical junction between the duodenum and the jejunum.

fimbria of uterine tubealso known as fimbria of fallopian tube; fimbriae of fallopian tube; fimbriae of uterine tube A fringe of tissue around the ostium of the fallopian tube, in the direction of the ovary.
left colic vein A portal vein that drains the descending colon. It is a tributary of the inferior mesenteric vein, and follows the path of its corresponding artery, the left colic artery.
right colic vein A portal vein that drains the ascending colon. It is a tributary of the superior mesenteric vein, and travels with its corresponding artery, the right colic artery.

left colic artery The first branch of the inferior mesenteric artery (IMA) is the left colic artery. The left colic artery supplies blood flow to the distal third of the transverse colon and the entirety of the descending colon. Once diverging from the IMA, the left colic artery runs anterior to the left ureter, left internal spermatic vessels (males), and psoas major before branching into its ascending and descending segments.

right colic artery The right colic artery may arise directly from the superior mesenteric artery (SMA) but often arises from a common trunk with the ileocolic artery or middle colic artery. It supplies the ascending colon.
intestinal junctionalso known as junction of intestine An anatomical junction between two parts of the intestine.

transition zone of prostatealso known as prostate transition zone The region of the prostate gland anterior to the central and peripheral zones, surrounding the proximal urethra. It is the zone of the human prostate gland that grows the most throughout life, and is responsible for benign prostatic hypertrophy.

peripheral zone of prostatealso known as prostate peripheral zone The region of the prostate that is located posterior to the central and transition zones, surrounding the distal urethra. It is the zone of origin for the vast majority of human prostatic cancers.

central zone of prostatealso known as prostate central zone The region of the prostate gland that is located between the peripheral and transition zones, surrounding the ejaculatory ducts. It gives rise to a very small percentage of human prostate cancers, often aggressive and invading the seminal vesicles.

trabecular sinus of lymph nodealso known as lymph node trabecular sinus The trabecular sinus is the lymph-filled space outside the trabeculae between lobules of the lymph node. This is a continuation of the subcapsular sinus which receives the afferent vessels and is present beneath the capsule. This space is traversed by both reticular fibers and cells in the lymph.
lymph node veinalso known as hilar vein of lymph node; vein of lymph node A vein where lymph node venules condense and which exits at the lymph node hilum. It is also called hilar vein.
lymph node arteryalso known as artery of lymph node; hilar artery of lymph node An artery that enters the lymph node at the hilum and branches into smaller arterioles.
medullary arteriole of lymph nodealso known as arteriole of medulla of lymph node An arteriole that arises from the hilar artery of a lymph node and radiates centrifugally, branching in the medulla.

medullary venule of lymph nodealso known as venule of medulla of lymph node Medullary venules are a continuation of high endothelial venules which condense repeatedly in the interfollicular cortex and peripheral deep cortical unit and then transition to medullary venules at the corticomedullary junction. The medullary venules condense and return centripetally to the hilar vein.

high endothelial venule High endothelial venules are specialized blood vessels adapted for lymphocyte trafficking. They form a spatially organized network, which controls both the type of lymphocyte and the site of entry into lymphoid tissues. Uniquely, high endothelial venules express vascular addressins that regulate lymphocyte entry into lymphoid organs. They perform this function in all lymphoid organs except the spleen.
high endothelial venule of lymph nodealso known as lymph node high endothelial venule A high endothelial venule that is part of a of lymph node.
venule of lymph nodealso known as lymph node venule A venule that is part of a lymph node.
arteriole of lymph nodealso known as lymph node arteriole An arteriole that is part of a lymph node.
bronchus submucosal glandalso known as bronchial submucosal gland; submucosal bronchial gland; submucosal bronchus gland A submucosal gland located in a bronchus.

lymph node germinal center light zonealso known as light zone of lymph node germinal center Lymph node germinal centers contain two microenvironments: the light zone and the dark zone. The light zone is sparsely populated with B cells and includes additional cell types such as follicular dendritic cells, lymph node tingible macrophages and T follicular helper cells.

lymph node germinal center dark zonealso known as dark zone of lymph node germinal center Lymph node germinal centers contain two microenvironments: the light zone and the dark zone. The dark zone is densely populated with B cell blasts and reticular cells.
myenteric nerve plexus of colon Myenteric nerve plexus that is located in the colon.
submucous nerve plexus of colon Submucous nerve plexus that is located in the colon.
parasympathetic cholinergic nerve A parasympathetic nerve that releases acetylcholine.
myenteric nerve plexus of small intestine Myenteric nerve plexus that is part of the small intestine.
submucous nerve plexus of small intestine Submucous nerve plexus that is located in the small intestine.

lymph node paracortex The lymph node paracortex is the middle layer of the lymph node and is mostly populated by T cells and dendritic cells. The paracortex also contains specialised blood vessels called high endothelial venules which allow lymphocytes to enter the node.

lymph node interfollicular cortexalso known as interfollicular cortex of lymph node Follicules in the lymph node are surrounded and separated by the interfollicular cortex. Together with the lymph node follicle, the interfollicular cortex of the lymph node lobule make up the superficial cortex of the lymph node. Capillaries empty into the high endothelial venules located in the interfollicular cortex. The interfollicular cortex also serves as transit corriders for lymphocytes migrating between the B and T cell areas.

subcapsular sinus ceilingalso known as ceiling of subcapsular sinus of lymph node; floor of capsule of lymph node; subcapsular sinus of lymph node ceiling The section of the lymph node capsule that faces the subcapsular sinus. In human, it's characterized by specific protein markers.

subcapsular sinus flooralso known as ceiling of cortex of lymph node; floor of subcapsular sinus of lymph node; subcapsular sinus of lymph node floor The section of the lymph node cortex that faces the subcapsular sinus. In human, it's characterized by specific protein markers.
medullary region of kidneyalso known as kidney medullary region A part of the kidney that comprises kidney pyramids and renal columns.
lymph node paracortical sinus A lymph node sinus intimately associated with paracortical cords that originate in the interfollicular cortex and extend into the medullary cords.
lymph node paracortical cord Lymph node paracortical parenchyma containing dense networks of T cells, B cells, fibroblastic reticular cells, and dendritic cells.
airway submucosal glandalso known as respiratory tract submucosal gland; submucosal gland of respiratory tract A submucosal gland found in a respiratory tract.

blood microvessel Any of the smallest blood vessels where blood circulates within organ tissues. Microvessels include terminal arterioles, metarterioles, capillaries, and venules (but exclude lymphatic capillaries). Arterioles carry oxygenated blood to the capillaries, and blood flows out of the capillaries through venules into veins.
egg follicle An individual reproductive unit containing a single oocyte and one or several layers of support cells (Armstrong et al., 2020).
excretory system An anatomical system that eliminates waste products that arise as a result of metabolic activity.

sublumbar lymph node A lymph node with a lymph center located within the caudal abdomen and pelvis, on the ventral side of the lumbar region. Includes the medial iliac, internal iliac (previously termed hypogastric) and sacral lymph nodes.
lobular bronchiolealso known as preterminal bronchiole A conductive airway that branches into terminal bronchioles.
visceral muscle tissuealso known as visceral muscle A muscle tissue that is associated with soft internal organs (viscera).
visceral striated muscle tissuealso known as striated visceral muscle tissue A striated muscle tissue that is associated with soft internal organs (viscera).
subsegmental bronchus Branch of conducting airway between a segmental bronchus and a preterminal bronchiole.
bronchial submucosal gland ciliated duct A ciliated duct part of a bronchial submucosal gland.
tracheal submucosal gland ciliated duct A ciliated duct part of a tracheal submucosal gland.
submucosal gland acinus A spherical or tubular structure in a submucosal gland that produces and secretes mucus and other substances into the ducts leading to the surface epithelium.
submucosal gland collecting duct A non-secretory tubular structure in the submucosal gland where secretions are collected before flowing towards the surface epithelium.
submucosal gland ciliated duct A ciliated tubular structure in a submucosal gland connecting the submucosal gland collecting duct with the surface epithelium.

bronchopulmonary segmentalso known as lung segment A discrete anatomical unit of the lung that is composed of a segmental bronchus and the lung tissue supplied by that bronchus. A bronchopulmonary segment exhibits a pyramidal shape, with its apex pointing towards the center of the lung and its base toward the pleural surface.

neuroendocrine system A regulatory system of the body that integrates the nervous system and the endocrine system. This system is formed by specialized neuroendocrine cells located mainly in the nervous system and neuroendocrine glands. However, they can also be found as either single cells or small clusters of cells dispersed throughout the surface epithelium of different tissues. The neuroendocrine system functions through the release of neurotransmitters and neurohormones, enabling communication between the endocrine and nervous systems to govern vitally important processes that include growth, reproduction, metabolism and energy homeostasis, electrolyte and water balance, and responses to stress.

placental basal platealso known as placenta basal plate A maternal facing structure of the placental disc, adjacent to the intervillous space. Major components of the placental basal plate include decidua basalis, fibrinoid, connective tissue, extravillous trophoblasts, and residues of degenerating villi and maternal vessels.

placental septumalso known as placenta septum An extension of the basal plate that protrudes into the intervillous space, creating a system of grooves which delimit elevated areas, also known as cotyledons or maternal lobes.
chorionic plate blood vessel A blood vessel that is part of the chorionic plate.

pulmonary interlobular septum A septum that surrounds and gives shape to the secondary pulmonary lobules, it is composed of connective tissue within which run the pulmonary veins and lymphatic vessels.

chorionic villous treealso known as placental villous tree A tree-like structure formed by chorionic villi that sprouts from the chorionic plate in the placental disc. The arborous shape of the chorionic villous tree provides maximal contact area with maternal blood in the intervillous space.

chorionic stem villusalso known as placental stem villus A chorionic villus that provides structural support to the villous tree. A chorionic stem villus is characterized by a condensed fibrous stroma in which fetal arteries, veins, arterioles, and venules are embedded. It represents a distributing framework for fetal chorionic circulation, supplying the floating villi. It can exhibit a diameter ranging from approximately 3000 μm (trunci near the chorionic plate) to 80 μm (smallest ramuli chorii).

chorionic mesenchymal villus The first generation of a tertiary villus that is derived from a syncytial sprout by the invasion of the mesenchyme, in which blood vessels differentiate through vasculogenesis, and gradually transforms into a new immature intermediate villus. A chorionic mesenchymal villus has a thick trophoblastic covering, and cytotrophoblast cells are interposed between syncytium and the trophoblastic basal lamina over 50–100% of the surface. The stroma is characterized by loosely arranged collagen fibers that enmesh mesenchymal and some villous macrophages. The fetal capillaries are poorly developed.

chorionic immature intermediate villus A bulbous, immature chorionic villus that is formed of loose connective tissue with few fetal vessels. A chorionic immature intermediate villus develops from a chorionic mesenchymal villus, and is the forerunner of a chorionic stem villus.

chorionic terminal villus The most distal part of a chorionic villus. A chorionic terminal villus is a grape-like structure characterized by a high degree of capillarization and highly dilated sinusoids. A terminal villus has less stroma and a discontinuous cytotrophoblast layer, and contains 4–6 fetal capillaries per cross section. It exhibits a diameter ranging from 40 to about 80 μm.

chorionic mature intermediate villus A slender branch of a chorionic stem villus. A chorionic mature intermediate villus lacks fetal arterioles and venules in the stroma, which is composed of slender fetal capillaries embedded into a loose connective tissue that is rich in cells but poor in fibers. It exhibits a diameter ranging from 60 to about 100 μm.
chorionic floating villus A chorionic villus that is not attached to the placental basal plate and it is immersed in maternal blood.

kidney loop of Henle long descending thin limb outer medullaalso known as long descending limb of the loop of Henle in the outer medulla A section of the long descending thin limb of the loop of Henle that is part of the outer medulla of the kidney.

kidney loop of Henle long descending thin limb inner medullaalso known as long descending limb of the loop of Henle in the inner medulla A section of the long descending thin limb of the loop of Henle that is part of the inner medulla of the kidney.

placental discalso known as placental disk A disc-shaped structure that is part of the placenta. A placental disc supports fetal development through the exchange of nutrients between maternal and fetal bloodstreams. The placental disc is structured to keep the blood streams separate, while maximizing surface area for the transport of nutrients between them, to maintain an immunological barrier.
chorionic villous mesenchyme A mesenchyme that is part of a chorionic villus.
chorionic stem villous blood vessel A blood vessel that is part of a chorionic stem villus.

chorionic terminal villous capillary A capillary that is part of a chorionic terminal villus. This capillary is generally narrow, but displays sinusoidal dilations along its length, often at the points of acute bends. These dilations bring the capillary endothelium into close contact with the overlying syncytiotrophoblast to form a vasculosyncytial membrane.
endometrial lymphatic vessel A lymphatic vessel that is part of an endometrium.
